pmc BMC Med Res Methodol BMC Med Res Methodol 43 bmcmrm BMC Medical Research Methodology 1471-2288 BMC PMC12481988 PMC12481988.1 12481988 12481988 41023832 10.1186/s12874-025-02650-x 2650 1 Research Modeling strategies for a flexible estimation of the crude cumulative incidence in the context of long follow-ups: model choice and predictive ability evaluation Biganzoli Giacomo giacomo.biganzoli@unimi.it 1 Marano Giuseppe 1 Boracchi Patrizia 1 2 1 https://ror.org/00wjc7c48 grid.4708.b 0000 0004 1757 2822 Unit of Medical Statistics and Bioinformatics, Department of Biomedical and Clinical Sciences (DIBIC), Università degli Studi di Milano, 2 https://ror.org/00wjc7c48 grid.4708.b 0000 0004 1757 2822 Data science research center (DSRC), Università degli Studi di Milano, 29 9 2025 2025 25 478401 217 5 11 2024 23 7 2025 29 09 2025 01 10 2025 01 10 2025 © The Author(s) 2025 2025 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Open Access http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Background Advancements in treatments for chronic diseases, such as breast cancer, have expanded our ability to observe patient outcomes beyond disease-related mortality, including events like distant recurrences. However, competing events can complicate the interpretation of primary outcomes, making the crude cumulative incidence function the most reliable measure for accurate follow-up analysis. Long-term studies require flexible modeling to accommodate intricate, time-dependent effects and interactions among covariates. Traditional models, such as the proportional sub-distribution hazards model, often insufficient to address these complexities. Although more adaptable methods have been proposed, there is still a need to systematically assess model complexity, particularly for exploratory purposes. This article presents a statistical learning workflow designed to evaluate model complexity in crude cumulative incidence and introduces a time-dependent metric for predictive accuracy. This framework provides researchers with an enhanced toolkit for robustly addressing the complexities of long-term outcome modeling and deriving interpretable prognostic algorithms. Methods We demonstrate our approach using data on time-to-distant breast cancer recurrences from the Milan 1 and Milan 3 trials, which have extensive follow-up periods. Two flexible modeling frameworks—pseudo-observations and sub-distribution hazard models—are employed, enhanced with spline functions to capture baseline hazard and risk. Our proposed workflow integrates graphical representations of Aalen-Johansen estimates for crude cumulative incidence, enabling researchers to visually hypothesize and adjust model complexity to match the studied phenomenon. Information criteria guide model selection to approximate the underlying data structure. Using bootstrapped data perturbations and time-dependent predictive accuracy measures, adjusted with Harrell’s optimism correction, we identify the optimal model structure, balancing explainability, predictivity, and generalizability. Results Our findings highlight the importance of data perturbation and validation through optimism-corrected predictive measures following the original data analysis. The initial model structure may differ from the most robust model identified through iterative perturbation. The ideal model has high robustness (most frequently selected in perturbations), strong explainability, and predictive capacity. When perturbation results are inconsistent, evaluating various time-dependent predictive measures offers additional insights, particularly regarding the trade-off between model complexity and predictive gains. In cases where predictive improvement is minimal, simpler and more explainable model structures are preferable. Conclusions The proposed statistical learning workflow, informed by domain expertise, allows for incorporating clinically relevant complexities in the prognostic modeling of distant recurrences in breast cancer. Our results suggest that, in many cases, a nuanced and flexible model structure may better serve future predictions than simpler models. This approach underscores the value of balancing model simplicity and complexity to achieve meaningful, clinically useful insights. Supplementary Information The online version contains supplementary material available at 10.1186/s12874-025-02650-x. Keywords Survival analysis Competing risks Flexible modeling pseudo-observations Generalized linear models pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement yes pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © BioMed Central Ltd., part of Springer Nature 2025 Background In clinical studies for assessing a therapeutic intervention on major diseases like cancer, overall survival (OS) is the endpoint validated and most objectively defined for the assessment of therapies [ 1 2 Among the various endpoints, clinical guidelines for breast cancer research define the distant recurrence-free survival (DRFS) on which researchers might want to evaluate the efficacy of a specific surgery protocol and/or adjuvant treatment and eventually compare different therapeutical strategies. Patients who receive treatment may experience various outcomes, such as new primary tumors (possibly unrelated to breast cancer) or death without clear evidence of disease recurrence, making it challenging to observe or interpret distant recurrences (DRs). In this situation, the action of the competing events (OTs or D) occurring first hinders the occurrence of DRs. In the context of competing risks, the crude cumulative incidence (CCI) function is the primary estimand of interest [ 3 4 5 6 Several papers focused on the estimation of CCI [ 7 10 11 12 The indirect approaches involve regressing the cause-specific hazard (CSH) or the SDH—the latter directly linked to CCI—on covariates and then using hazard estimates to compute CCI by exploiting their relationship. For the semi-parametric regression models, the shape of the baseline (cause-specific or sub-distribution) hazard function is a nuisance parameter [ 13 14 Oncology studies, especially with lengthy follow-up times, often involve complex interactions among covariates and non-linear and time-dependent effects of covariates on numerical measurement scale. Thus, the proportionality assumption of SDH, cumulative incidence of events, or odds of events may not hold [ 15 16 17 Researchers might apply formal hypothesis tests to detect the non-proportionality of hazards and interaction effects. In contrast, others, in an exploratory framework, might base their choice solely on minimizing information criteria [ 18 Alternatively, some researchers focus only on measures of predictive ability, such as discrimination and calibration, alongside internal and external validation procedures [ 19 20 The most popular measure of discrimination is the area under the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve (AUC) [ 21 22 23 24 25 26 Model discrimination and calibration may give additional helpful information in modeling complex effects, such as assessing the robustness of a model structure investigated. Indeed, they can be employed to evaluate how critical the inclusion of complex time-dependent and interaction effects in the model selection step is for predictive accuracy at the individual level. Although information criteria serve as indicators of model discrimination, they are somewhat incomparable since they lack a defined minimum (absence of discrimination) and maximum (perfect discrimination). Given the numerous methods available for selecting model complexity, an important consideration is how to effectively combine these methodologies to identify a robust model that captures the complexity of the phenomenon under study and remains interpretable. Additionally, it is beneficial to examine whether the performance of this integrated model complexity selection approach, which leverages information from the aforementioned methods, differs between the two primary quantities—on the instantaneous scale for the SDH and directly on the cumulative scale for the pseudo-observation approach—for estimating the CCI function mentioned earlier. In this work, we propose a workflow to analyze data in a competing risk framework where CCI is the measure of interest and complex effects are expected. Particularly, we propose and illustrate a method to evaluate the performance of different model structures in light of to the aforementioned issues. To this end, we analyze data from two historical breast cancer clinical trials [ 27 28 The analysis must account for possible time-dependent effects of both treatment and axillary nodal status and the interaction effect between treatment and nodal status. Two methods of obtaining estimates of CCI of distant recurrences will be utilized and compared: (1) an indirect approach based on modeling the discrete-time SDH model [ 29 For simplicity, we will use standard regression splines to specify a smooth function of time, and we will consider classic information criteria—AIC and the Quasi-Information Criterion (QIC)— for the model selection step [ 18 30 Methods Figure 1 Fig. 1 Scheme of the rationale and the modeling framework proposed Target functions in the competing risks framework At the beginning of the follow-up period, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
