lected only 1.5% of the time ( b The pseudo-observation modeling framework -with the number of time-points selected for computing the pseudo-observation and the type of spline adopted- seem to favor lower levels of complexity than the SDH counterpart. In the Milan 1 cohort, the modulation effect of nodal status on treatment effect remains evident but is less robust at 68%, and the selection of time-dependent effects is infrequent. In the Milan 3 cohort, the interaction effect is robust at 75%, although 25% of the time, the additive model is chosen. The data perturbation procedure did not definitively identify a single most robust model structure. Additional insights on the practical utility of considering more complex model structures still selected by the algorithm based on the information criteria might be derived by the assessment of their predictive ability. The specification of the SDH baseline in Milan 1 required mostly the selection of three interior knots (7 spline basis), regardless the model structure complexity. The specification of the SDH baseline of Milan 3 showed a greater variability of selection. On the contrary, for the baseline risk function of both Milan 1 and Milan 3, 3 knots (2 basis) were mostly preferred indicating that more complexity was not needed. Time-dependent measures of discrimination The discriminatory capacity in relation to model complexity displays no relevant differences between the pseudo-observations and SDH modeling frameworks. Figure 6 a b Fig. 6 Time-dependent discriminatory capacity of the model structures assessed by means of time-dependent C-index. In ( a b c d Conversely, in the Milan 3 trial cohort, the additive model displays the lowest value, while multiplicative models, with or without a time-dependent effect of nodal status and treatment, demonstrate the highest discriminant ability ( c d In the SDH modeling framework, for Milan 1, Model Structure 4, despite showing lower discriminatory ability, is the structure tha